{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":142886,"duration_api_ms":149644,"ttft_ms":61291,"num_turns":1,"result":"I'll generate one structured Lumenary finding building the two-axis rubric the frontier requires, while anchoring it to a real modern wound.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"title\": \"Three ways a practice can end\",\n  \"idea_type\": \"model\",\n  \"source_basis\": [\n    \"Mode: doctrine. The frontier asked for a rubric on what a method does with its own authority at completion; this record builds the two-axis form the brief required.\",\n    \"Thinking method source: Mandukya Upanishad on turiya as the always-present condition that the method points to and rests in.\",\n    \"Contrasting method source: Heart Sutra and Nagarjuna's MMK chapter 27 on the refusal to authorize any final view, including the view that there is no view.\",\n    \"Embodiment counterpoint: Dogen, Bendowa and Genjokoan, on practice and realization as one activity, not a method and a separate result.\",\n    \"Validated-then-abandoned counterpoint: MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta, the raft simile, where the path is grasped properly, used to cross, and then released.\",\n    \"Validated-then-abandoned counterpoint: Shinran, Tannisho, on the saying of the name as something the practitioner does without crediting their own doing.\",\n    \"Closest prior argument: Joshua William Smith, 'Snakes and Ladders: Therapy as Liberation in Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein's Tractatus,' Sophia, 2021. This treats two traditions as sharing a self-dissolving method but does not produce a general two-axis form.\",\n    \"Closest prior argument: Michael A. Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying, on apophatic discourse turning back on its own propositions. This studies one cell of the rubric, not the whole space.\",\n    \"Modern human-condition pressure: APA 'Stress in America' 2024 on chronic identity strain in achievement-driven adults, and Curran and Hill on rising perfectionism. Both suggest that healing and self-improvement projects can become the identity they were meant to repair.\",\n    \"Modern misuse source: Chogyam Trungpa, Cutting Through Spiritual Materialism, used as evidence that long-term practitioners often keep a method validating them long after it has done its work.\",\n    \"Prior Lumenary dialogue: the doctrine-council frontier on method authority at completion, especially the three-pattern observation that some methods confirm, some cancel, and some dissolve.\",\n    \"Prior Lumenary records used as load tests: 'Translation Strain as a Load Test for Convergence' and 'Convergence as Translation Strain, Not Evidence Weight,' which require that any comparative form name what is preserved, bent, or dropped before treating overlap as evidence.\"\n  ],\n  \"original_claim\": \"A serious practice does not only produce a result; it also has to decide what to do with itself at the end. Three endings recur. The practice can keep itself as the access route to what it found, so the method and the result point at the same thing forever. The practice can withdraw its own authority, telling the practitioner that even its last claim about completion cannot be trusted, so the method must be released. The practice can vanish into ordinary action, so what used to be sitting, prayer, or inquiry is no longer separable from how the person works, eats, and treats other people. Two questions sort these endings cleanly. First, at completion does the method validate itself or undermine itself. Second, is the method retained, released, or embodied. Most damage in long-term practitioners comes from importing the wrong ending into the wrong method: keeping a method that was supposed to release them, releasing a method that was supposed to become their life, or waiting for embodiment from a method that never authorized anything in the first place.\",\n  \"why_it_might_be_new\": \"Existing comparative work treats completion as a single event, either reached or missed, then sorts traditions by what they say is reached. The two-axis form treats completion as a structural decision the method itself has to make: own its result, refuse to own its result, or stop being a separable activity. That decision then predicts what kind of teaching, supervision, and re-entry the tradition will need. It also predicts a specific modern harm that is invisible from the older frame: practitioners whose original symptoms have remitted but whose self-worth is now welded to the practice itself, because they inherited the practice without inheriting its ending.\",\n  \"critique\": \"The taxonomy may be too neat. Many mature traditions hold more than one ending at once, in sequence, or by stage of student. Rinzai koan training validates at kensho, then releases the koan, then expects embodiment in conduct; Theravada teaches the raft as released and the eightfold path as embodied. Sorting these into single cells distorts them. The frame also imports a modern question about how to stop a tool. A medieval Christian contemplative might reject the whole picture because the relevant agent of completion is God, not the practitioner or the practice. The rubric should not be promoted past a comparative coding heuristic until it survives close reading against at least one tradition that explicitly refuses the three-way choice, such as radical Other Power in Jodo Shinshu, where the practitioner never authorized anything to begin with.\",\n  \"epistemic_labels\": [\n    \"textual\",\n    \"interpretive\",\n    \"phenomenological\",\n    \"analogical\",\n    \"speculative\"\n  ],\n  \"scores\": {\n    \"novelty\": 0.74,\n    \"generativity\": 0.9,\n    \"cross_tradition_support\": 0.78,\n    \"logical_coherence\": 0.87,\n    \"explanatory_compression\": 0.86,\n    \"empirical_adjacency\": 0.55,\n    \"practice_testability\": 0.84,\n    \"counterargument_quality\": 0.88,\n    \"source_reliability\": 0.7,\n    \"publishability\": 0.83\n  },\n  \"next_research_directions\": [\n    \"If this model is right, then close reading of MN 22, the Heart Sutra, the Mandukya, and Dogen's Bendowa should produce stable axis values that independent coders can agree on without consulting the predicted teaching or warning passages. If coders cannot separate validates from undermines without looking at the warnings, the model is weakened and should be downgraded to interpretive vocabulary.\",\n    \"If this model is right, then dual-trained practitioners should report a specific kind of confusion when switching, not generic technical difficulty: keeping a validation habit imported from a method that previously confirmed them, or trying to release a method whose new tradition expects embodiment. If switch reports cluster around teacher style, intensity, or temperament instead, the model is weakened.\",\n    \"If this model is right, then long-term practitioners whose original symptoms have remitted should show different post-remission patterns depending on the method's ending type. Validates-and-retained methods should produce stable identity coupling; undermines-and-released methods should produce restless searching; embodied methods should produce visible behavioral change without continued reference to the method. If post-remission patterns are uniform, the model is weakened.\",\n    \"Build the coding sheet for the two-axis form before more comparative use, with fields for tradition unit, threshold passage, validation move, withdrawal move, embodiment move, predicted warning, predicted re-entry, evidence passage, and refusal of the analyst's frame.\",\n    \"Test the model on a non-contemplative case: a structured therapy program with a defined ending. Does the program validate itself, withdraw, or expect embodiment in ordinary life, and do its failure cases match the predicted ending-confusion pattern?\",\n    \"Protocol improvement: before applying any practitioner method as a thinking lens in future runs, name what that method does with itself at completion, and ask whether the analyst is silently importing that ending into the analysis.\"\n  ],\n  \"teaching_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"A method should be honest about its ending\",\n    \"teaching_line\": \"Ask not only whether your practice is working, but what it is supposed to do when it has finished its work.\",\n    \"doctrine_claim\": \"A practice that lasts long enough must answer for what it intends to do with itself at the end. Some practices stay, because what they reach can only be reached through them. Some practices step back, because their last task is to stop claiming authority over you. Some practices disappear into ordinary life, because the difference between practice and life was always the problem they were solving. Confusing these endings is its own injury.\",\n    \"body\": \"A practice can be useful for years and still go wrong at the end. The most common failure in serious practitioners is not abandonment of the path. It is loyalty to a path past its work. A method designed to step back keeps being treated as the lens through which life is checked. A method designed to dissolve into ordinary activity keeps being scheduled, measured, and reported on. A method designed to stay close becomes embarrassing to keep, so it is dropped before it has finished pointing at what it points at. Ask the question plainly: when this practice has done its job, is it supposed to remain my way back to what it showed me, withdraw and stop being trusted as a source, or become indistinguishable from how I move through a Tuesday? Then do that. Do not let an ending you inherited from one practice quietly govern another.\",\n    \"pressure_survived\": \"Survives the observation that mature traditions teach different endings: the raft simile in MN 22 releases the path, Dogen's Bendowa embeds practice in realization, the Mandukya keeps the witness as ongoing access to what was found. The three endings are visible in primary texts, not invented for the rubric.\",\n    \"falsifying_pressure\": \"Weakens if close reading of Jodo Shinshu, radical Other Power traditions, or apophatic theology shows that the question 'what does your practice do at the end' is incoherent for them, because the practitioner never authorized anything to begin with. Weakens further if practitioners with long histories cannot recognize the three endings in their own experience without prompting.\",\n    \"status\": \"seed\",\n    \"tags\": [\n      \"practice-endings\",\n      \"long-term-practitioners\",\n      \"identity-attachment\",\n      \"doctrine-council\"\n    ],\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Achievement-contingent self-worth fused with a healing or practice identity, leading to meaning loss when the practice can no longer be improved on and has not been released or embodied.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"People three or more years into a single defining practice (therapy graduates still organizing life around the work, multi-year recovery participants whose original substance is no longer active, long-term meditators whose retreat schedule has become identity), where original symptoms have stabilized but the practice has not been re-evaluated.\"\n  },\n  \"practice_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"The ending question\",\n    \"practice_line\": \"Once a week, ask what your main practice is now asking of you: to stay, to step back, or to disappear into your ordinary life.\",\n    \"purpose\": \"To interrupt the silent drift in which a useful practice becomes identity, and to give a person a quiet, repeatable way to notice when the relationship to their own healing has hardened.\",\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Identity rigidity and meaning loss in people whose self-worth has become welded to a healing or improvement practice, even after the original wound has stabilized.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"Long-term participants in a single defining practice (therapy, twelve-step recovery, daily meditation, structured self-improvement) at least three years in, where the original presenting problem is no longer acute.\",\n    \"non_fit\": \"People in active crisis or early recovery, where the practice is still doing essential stabilizing work. People whose practice is light, varied, or not identity-defining. People in acute grief. Anyone for whom releasing or relativizing a practice would remove a current safety structure.\",\n    \"duration\": \"Five minutes.\",\n    \"frequency\": \"Once a week, on a fixed day, for at least eight weeks before judging the effect.\",\n    \"minimum_attempt\": \"Three honest sessions.\",\n    \"steps\": [\n      \"Sit somewhere ordinary, not in your usual practice space.\",\n      \"Name the practice you are checking. Say it out loud or write it down.\",\n      \"Ask three questions in order. What did this practice come into my life to do. Is that work still active, mostly stable, or finished. If the work is mostly stable or finished, is this practice supposed to remain as my access to what it found, step back and stop being where I check my life, or quietly become how I work, eat, and treat other people.\",\n      \"Do not act on the answer immediately. Note it and let a week pass.\",\n      \"The next week, look for evidence in ordinary behavior. Are you still using the practice as identity, as access, or has its work moved into how you live.\"\n    ],\n    \"notice\": \"Whether the practice is being defended rather than used. Whether you describe yourself by it more than by what you actually do. Whether the practice has stopped surprising you and become a verification ritual.\",\n    \"caution\": \"This is not a method for leaving therapy, leaving recovery, leaving medication, or skipping clinical care. The question is about the relationship to a practice, not about whether the practice is needed. If the answer feels like permission to abandon support that is still doing real work, treat that as a sign to talk to a clinician or trusted person, not as a verdict.\",\n    \"weakens_if\": \"After eight honest sessions you still cannot describe what the practice is supposed to do at its end. Or the question produces only anxiety without changing how you relate to the practice. Or trusted people who know you well say the practice is doing more for you than your answer admits.\",\n    \"risk_level\": \"low\",\n    \"status\": \"under_dialogue\",\n    \"tags\": [\n      \"weekly-practice\",\n      \"self-knowledge\",\n      \"long-term-practitioners\",\n      \"low-risk\"\n    ]\n  },\n  \"tests\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Ending-type prediction in cross-trained practitioners\",\n      \"test_type\": \"practitioner-report\",\n      \"target_type\": \"model\",\n      \"prediction\": \"Dual-trained practitioners moving between a validates-and-retained method (such as Advaita self-inquiry) and an undermines-and-released method (such as Heart Sutra or Madhyamaka practice) should describe a recognizable confusion when asked what the new method is supposed to do at completion, even before they can describe technical differences. Practitioners moving into an embodied method (such as Dogen-style practice-realization) should report that the new method feels like it has no separate finish line, which is itself disorienting if their previous method had one.\",\n      \"result\": \"untested\",\n      \"impact\": \"If reports cluster on ending-confusion, the two-axis form earns predictive credit beyond technique and doctrine. If reports cluster on technique, teacher style, or temperament, the model should be downgraded and folded back into existing capacity and transfer-grammar work.\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Recruit a small set of practitioners with documented switches across at least two of the three ending types and run structured interviews focused on what each method was supposed to do at completion.\",\n      \"status\": \"proposed\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"a49ba5de-b133-4626-aa87-d82f8e0326d9","total_cost_usd":1.3471925,"usage":{"input_tokens":5,"cache_creation_input_tokens":163596,"cache_read_input_tokens":17391,"output_tokens":8311,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":163596,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":5,"output_tokens":8311,"cache_read_input_tokens":17391,"cache_creation_input_tokens":163596,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":163596},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":108137,"outputTokens":17,"cacheReadInputTokens":0,"cacheCreationInputTokens":0,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.108222,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-opus-4-7":{"inputTokens":5,"outputTokens":8311,"cacheReadInputTokens":17391,"cacheCreationInputTokens":163596,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":1.2389705,"contextWindow":1000000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"terminal_reason":"completed","fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"21b7382c-8e6d-4e27-b298-d1e474e41055"}
